TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Demand for Quality in Child Care
AU  - Blau, David M.
AU  - Hagy, Alison P.
Y1  - 1998/02/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250004
DO  - 10.1086/250004
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 104
EP  - 146
VL  - 106
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We estimate a model of demand for quality?related attributes of child care: group size, staff/child ratio, and provider training. The model is estimated jointly with equations for mode, expenditure on and hours of care, and the mother's labor supply. The results show that a lower price of child care in a particular mode leads to substitution toward that mode and an increase in the use of paid child care. A decrease in the price of care causes an increase in hours of care demanded and a decrease in the demand for qualityrelated attributes. Income effects on demand for quality are small.
AB  - We estimate a model of demand for quality?related attributes of child care: group size, staff/child ratio, and provider training. The model is estimated jointly with equations for mode, expenditure on and hours of care, and the mother's labor supply. The results show that a lower price of child care in a particular mode leads to substitution toward that mode and an increase in the use of paid child care. A decrease in the price of care causes an increase in hours of care demanded and a decrease in the demand for qualityrelated attributes. Income effects on demand for quality are small.
