TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bettors Love Skewness, Not Risk, at the Horse Track
AU  - Golec, Joseph
AU  - Tamarkin, Maurry
Y1  - 1998/02/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250007
DO  - 10.1086/250007
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 205
EP  - 225
VL  - 106
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Studies of horse race betting have empirically established a long shot anomaly; that is, low?probabiliy, high?variance bets (long shots) provide low mean returns and high?probability, lowvariance bets provide relatively high mean returns. Because bettors willingly accept low?return, high?variance bets, researchers conclude that bettors are risk lovers. In this study, we show that the data are at least as consistent with risk aversion as they are with risk loving when one explicitly considers the skewness of bet returns. Because the variance and skewness of bet returns are highly correlated, bettors may appear to prefer variance when it is skewness that they crave.
AB  - Studies of horse race betting have empirically established a long shot anomaly; that is, low?probabiliy, high?variance bets (long shots) provide low mean returns and high?probability, lowvariance bets provide relatively high mean returns. Because bettors willingly accept low?return, high?variance bets, researchers conclude that bettors are risk lovers. In this study, we show that the data are at least as consistent with risk aversion as they are with risk loving when one explicitly considers the skewness of bet returns. Because the variance and skewness of bet returns are highly correlated, bettors may appear to prefer variance when it is skewness that they crave.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250007
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250007
Y2  - 2024/03/22
